    # [Scene: City Archive & Council Hall | Night]

    scene bg ch14_77428d_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A raw, insistent low string; a single bow drawn hard and never released]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant thunder rumble under the glass; a microphone with a faint, nervous feedback hum]
    "You stand at the center of the council chamber and feel the room as a pressure against your ribs. The red light over the recording console blinks as if keeping time with a pulse you no"
    "longer control. Every conversation you have carried — every meeting, every midnight edit, every compromise — has braided itself into this quiet, terrible instrument: one decision that will reverberate through Harrow Bay."
    "You can taste metal on your tongue. The air is heavy with the brine that has begun to climb the stone steps outside, a reminder that the sea has patience and will take what we leave unguarded."
    show maya_soren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soren "This clause is non-negotiable.' (You place the paper on the lectern so that everyone can see the bolded section.) 'Enforcement language, milestones, independent auditors, community oversight panels — real, binding mechanisms. Without them, there is no contract."
    show asha_reed at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_reed "You've written it like a warning, Maya. They'll call it a poison pill. They'll use it to stall."
    "You hold the outline of the clause with fingers that are not steady. You know what stalling feels like: another rainy season, another house raised on stilts that no longer rests on its people. The option to buy time with tools that sideline people is a familiar, dangerous lullaby."
    show jonah_mek at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_mek "People in Lower Quay will want assurances,' Jonah says, palms flat on the mahogany table. His voice is low, almost private. 'We can schedule the labor commitments into the city's work orders, put them on payroll. That buys trust."
    hide maya_soren
    show elias_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_voss "And it buys ignorance if we wait too long. The contractor's deployment—if delayed by six months—we lose beach profile, we lose habitat edge, and the storms in the forecast will carve us open.' He looks at you and then away, jaw tight. 'I can't sleep thinking what happens if we do nothing."
    "You have heard Elias's argument a hundred ways, heard the tautness behind each sentence: optimism braided with fear. He is not a villain; he is someone who remembers the sea as both cradle and threat and"
    "wants to shove something in its mouth to slow it down. You understand him. You also understand the hard ledger of history — who pays when 'help' arrives that is not also accountable."
    hide asha_reed
    show maya_soren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soren "I know what happens when infrastructure arrives without oversight,' you say. 'I know who gets displaced. I'm not willing to trade people's homes for vague promises. If the contractor won't accept the enforcement language, we reject their bid. We put the project on a slower, community-controlled path."
    hide jonah_mek
    show asha_reed at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_reed "Finally.' She leans forward, eyes a white-hot focus. 'You mean it."

    elias_voss "You know what that will do. Funding dries up if the company walks. Equipment sits. People die if we don't act in time."
    "The words hang like thunderheads. You feel the chamber narrow, every face a map of consequence. Asha's relief shudders across the room like a gust. Elias's fear becomes an accusation and then a plea. Jonah looks like he is carrying a threshold between them—wooden, heavy, warping in wet."
    hide elias_voss
    hide maya_soren
    hide asha_reed

    scene bg ch14_77428d_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings staccato, heartbeat percussion; the tempo quickens]

    menu:
        "Step forward and read the clause aloud, intentionally sharp":
            "You clear your throat and read each enforcement measure like a verdict. The room stiffens; even the recorder seems to hold its breath."
        "Let Jonah speak next, let him untangle the labor clause":
            "You nod to Jonah. His voice grounds the room with practical detail and small promises that sound like planks against open water."

