    "Continue"
    # [Scene: Council Hall — Continued | Night]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant chanting begins to rise outside — muffled, then closer; someone bangs a pan in protest on the stone steps]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A layered dissonance. The tempo becomes a march.]
    "Outside, the city is awake with noise. Inside, the council chamber becomes a battlefield of tongues. The contractor's representatives are not present — the decision to reject them comes from within the room — but their"
    "absence is a presence of its own: a hollow of power that feels almost like dereliction. People will interpret the silence in ways you cannot control."
    show asha_reed at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_reed "We need a community oversight board with real teeth. Not just a committee — people who can stop work if audits fail.' (She points, fingers like stakes.) 'No private hellscapes of profit. No displacement."
    show jonah_mek at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_mek "Bind the labor. Make pay transparent. Put community courtrooms on-site to hear disputes quickly.' (He lists specifics like a carpenter naming tools.) 'If you make it enforceable, they'll be able to trust the work."
    show elias_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_voss "I will help—I'll pivot my designs to smaller-scale modules we can deploy locally. If the big deployment stalls, I won't walk away. But don't leave me to argue to nobody while the bay eats itself."
    "His voice, raw and pleading, cracks something inside you. You think of nights on boats, of the creak of hulls and the salt-slick air. You think of the faces in Lower Quay, of Rosa's hands in"
    "the soil. You think of the obligation that has always been yours: to protect not just land, but the right of people to belong to it."
    hide asha_reed
    show maya_soren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soren "Then we codify it. We build the oversight board now. We write penalties into the contract that are automatic and enforceable — not suggestions, not aspirations.' (Your words land like stones.) 'We slow this deployment because sovereignty is worth delay."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single thunderclap outside; a window shakes in its frame]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Screech of strings that resolves into a low, mournful chord]
    "The room does not erupt in applause. It fractures into more complicated noises: whispers of relief, sharp breaths of anger, a low beginning-of-march hum as cameras click and the city hears. For every hand that lifts"
    "in quiet approval there's a mouth that opens in protest. The city begins to rearrange itself around the choice you just made."
    # [Scene: Community Gardens (Lower Quay) | Dawn]
    hide jonah_mek
    hide elias_voss
    hide maya_soren

    scene bg ch14_77428d_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, single notes slow and heavy]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain hitting plastic sheeting; the distant roar of trucks rerouting]
    "You come to the gardens before the sun because you need the dirt under your nails. The night left the neighborhood hollow with rumor and fear. Here, the fight turns human in its smallest details —"
    "who tends the beds, who gets paid, who keeps a roof over their head while machines idle."
    show rosa_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_calder "You chose the hard way, child.' Her hands are knotted with soil and age. 'It will sting for a stretch. But people stay. That is still the anchor."
    show jonah_mek at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_mek "I'll get the payroll in order,' he tells you. 'We can keep folks working on raised-bed retrofits, shoreline plantings, shorelines we know how to tend. It won't be as fast, but it's honest work."
    "There are faces in the crowd that mirror the city itself: lined, washed, determined. Some glance at you with gratitude; others with suspicion. You understand the suspicion — leaders who promise and fail are memories that last like scars. Your throat closes with the weight of other people's histories."
    show elias_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_voss "I made a list,' he says, voice small. 'Micro-modules, kelp nets you can hang from the pilings, community sensors we can build together. We'll run tests in tight cycles. We don't have to stop thinking big — we have to start thinking together."
    "He sets down sketches, wet ink bleeding into the margins like the city itself. You look at the pages — smaller interventions, repair kits, teaching sessions. They promise less spectacle and more survival. Your chest tightens"
    "on the clarity of it: the scale of sacrifice required is larger than any one person but composed of small, repeated choices."

    menu:
        "Walk the rows with Rosa and listen to her stories":
            "You bend to the soil beside her. Her stories are salt and seed and memory; you can feel the continuity of place anchoring your resolve."
        "Help Elias catalog components for the micro-modules":
            "You take the pen and begin marking parts, your handwriting a map of next steps. The act of making a list steadies you."

