    # [Scene: Rooftop Workshop | Late Afternoon]
    hide rosa_calder
    hide jonah_mek
    hide elias_voss

    scene bg ch14_77428d_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Machines humming; a rhythm of industrious, anxious energy]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soldering hiss, a radio muttering weather updates]
    "The deployment has slowed. Equipment sits in ports and warehouses like wounded things. Funding wobbles. Vendors threaten legal action. Protests line the promenade. You have enforced the clause; the city breathes in a different way—rougher, more ragged, but honest."
    show elias_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_voss "I don't regret pivoting.' He passes you a coil of reclaimed netting. 'This will be for the shoreline trials. If we do this right, we'll have living defenses people can replicate themselves."
    show maya_soren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soren "You could have walked,"

    elias_voss "I almost did. But I realized I'd rather build with you than be right from afar.' He pauses. 'I can't fix everything, Maya. But I can keep trying. So can you."
    "He leans close to fasten a clip, the smell of solder and salt mixing in the air. Your chest is a drum. The city outside is frayed — but here, in this messy workshop, a different kind of hope feels as brittle as glass and twice as determined."
    show asha_reed at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_reed "We will watch them,' she says. 'We will hold them to the letter. If the contractors try to slip their way back with loopholes, we'll be the ones who know and name it.' Her voice is steady but not soft. 'I am not folding. This is our right."
    hide elias_voss
    show jonah_mek at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_mek "We need enforcement teams,' he says. 'Local auditors, community liaisons, legal clinics. People trained to read contracts so they don't get sold.' He looks at you, the plan in his hands like a plank. 'We make the machinery of oversight ourselves."
    "There is anger at the edges of every plan — at companies that would treat the city like a ledger, at politicians who mark votes in pencil. The anger is righteous, and it feeds the work."
    "But underneath it, there is a wound you feel like a pulse: the cost that must be paid in time and money and the quiet erosion of faith."
    hide maya_soren
    hide asha_reed
    hide jonah_mek

    scene bg ch14_77428d_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendo of strings, then a sudden, breathless silence]
    "You have made the call. The enforcement clause is written into the city's charter for this project. You rejected the contractor that would not accept it. You made a choice that slows the pace of protection so that the protection belongs to those it is meant to serve."
    "You think of the faces you've failed previously — the garden you moved years ago, the pots of rosemary that never sprouted where you said they would. The memory of that compromise sits in your chest like a stone."
    show maya_soren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soren "We will be judged by what we keep and what we refuse to give up."
    "The judgement is already arriving. The city murmurs and shouts and files complaints and makes plans. Some call it the safe path; others call it cowardice. Some will never forgive the delay; others will never forget the fact of ownership."
    hide maya_soren

    scene bg ch14_77428d_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant sirens, layered with the sound of waves hitting a reinforced pylon]
    "It is not a clean victory. The deployment slowed; storms still came at edges; some livelihoods were squeezed in the pause. But a new structure rises from the friction: a council reformed to include rotating seats"
    "for community auditors, a charter that binds the city's hands to the people's will, and a thousand small projects stitched together by neighbors who turned policy into practice."
    "Elias works at the kelp racks at dawn and the sensor benches at dusk. Asha keeps watch and leads trainings; she still yells when she must, but she stays. Jonah builds, steady as ever, turning plans"
    "into planks. You carry the cost of every delay and every saved life in the same hollow of your ribs."
    "You do not feel triumphant. There is grief baked into the victory like grit in bread. The air tastes like rain and salt and something harder — the knowledge that durable governance is not an event but a wound that will scar and need tending."
    "You step back onto the rooftop at dusk. Harrow Bay glows: patched lanterns, the slow blink of sensors, figures moving below like careful ghosts. The enforcement clause is a small, stubborn thing in the city's legal code now — a line someone can point to when power forgets itself."
    "You exhale. It is not relief. It is a breath taken to steady the hands that must keep working."

    scene bg ch14_77428d_7 at full_bg
